1
00:00:02,274 --> 00:00:05,980
Tonight I want to talk about the four foundations for mindfulness.

2
00:00:07,041 --> 00:00:10,387
In Pali this is the Satipatthana Sutta.

3
00:00:11,589 --> 00:00:19,542
Sutta means a teaching or a discourse and the Satipatthana Sutta is considered the jewel of all the Buddha's teachings.

4
00:00:20,196 --> 00:00:23,803
For the past few days we've been focusing on the Four Noble Truths.

5
00:00:24,923 --> 00:00:28,971
These describe the insights the Buddha discovered on his way to enlightenment.

6
00:00:30,032 --> 00:00:37,343
The Satipatthana Sutta tells us how to observe our experience in order to come to these very insights.

7
00:00:38,384 --> 00:00:40,347
It's the how-to of the Dhamma.

8
00:00:42,185 --> 00:00:54,625
It's often called the direct approach, by comparison to the indirect approach of Samatha meditation, which includes an extra step, generating a deep state of concentration and peacefulness.

9
00:00:56,067 --> 00:01:05,543
The meditation described in the Satipatthana Sutta is termed Vipassana, while the deeply peaceful states are termed Samatha Jhana.

10
00:01:06,721 --> 00:01:15,150
In this teaching, the Buddha clarifies that we do not need to attain the Samatha Jhana in order to have the insights necessary for liberation.

11
00:01:16,332 --> 00:01:23,382
This is really good news for lay people because the Samatha Jhana are best supported in secluded monastic conditions.

12
00:01:24,543 --> 00:01:29,269
By comparison, Vipassana is possible even when we are living a busy life.

13
00:01:30,328 --> 00:01:37,540
Perhaps to emphasize this, the Buddha addressed the Satipatthana Sutta, the jewel of his teachings, to lay people.

14
00:01:38,581 --> 00:01:49,957
It was given when he visited the town of Kamasadama and was impressed by how diligently the native Kuru people were practicing mindfulness in their ordinary daily lives.

15
00:01:51,591 --> 00:02:02,331
Although the Buddha refers to the meditator as a Bhikkhu, which nowadays only refers to an ordained monk, it originally referred to anyone who practiced the Dhamma.

16
00:02:04,436 --> 00:02:07,962
Let's look for a moment at the word Satipatthana.

17
00:02:08,602 --> 00:02:11,866
The Pali word sati means mindfulness.

18
00:02:12,986 --> 00:02:23,240
The word patana is usually translated as foundation, but I like an alternative that Joseph Goldstein suggests, pasture.

19
00:02:24,961 --> 00:02:29,046
It evokes a pleasant image of the mind grazing in various pastures.

20
00:02:30,467 --> 00:02:34,193
This suggests restfulness, but also engagement.

21
00:02:34,913 --> 00:02:38,337
The mind isn't idly sunbathing in the pastures.

22
00:02:38,673 --> 00:02:56,765
it is finding and taking nourishment in each our journey to enlightenment involves nibbling and digesting the insights on offer when attention dwells in these pastures think of a rural landscape with gently undulating ground

23
00:02:56,998 --> 00:03:05,737
Our mind can rove around here and there, exploring all its little nooks and crannies, its bright patches and its shady copses.

24
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:12,331
There are mucky patches too, and marshes and rocky cliffs and perhaps thickets of briars.

25
00:03:13,294 --> 00:03:15,378
Our job is to get to know them all.

26
00:03:17,198 --> 00:03:27,401
Here and there in tonight's talk, I'm going to dovetail this teaching with that on the seven factors of enlightenment and with the wheel of dependent origination.

27
00:03:28,645 --> 00:03:30,229
So just a quick recap.

28
00:03:31,627 --> 00:03:36,913
The wheel describes the 12-step process leading from ignorance to dukkha.

29
00:03:37,914 --> 00:03:57,498
The gardening image is a helpful way to remember the wheel, all the problems starting with the whirlwind of ignorance, carrying in seeds of sankara, which can then implant themselves and grow up to become a bed of weeds, which are themselves decaying and dying when we come to our final step of dukkha.

30
00:03:59,268 --> 00:04:03,335
The seven factors are the beautiful qualities we develop in meditation.

31
00:04:04,156 --> 00:04:05,558
Remember our wild geese?

32
00:04:06,941 --> 00:04:09,284
These give an image for the seven factors.

33
00:04:10,526 --> 00:04:14,272
Mindfulness is in the lead supported by two flanks.

34
00:04:15,335 --> 00:04:22,827
There is a wide flank eager to push ahead and a slipstream flank calming everything down.

35
00:04:25,036 --> 00:04:40,411
If you want to put all three images together, think of our job in meditation being to get those wild geese into our pastures to nibble away at the seedlings before they grow into a thicket of briars and thistles.

36
00:04:43,177 --> 00:04:49,384
Before describing each of the pastures, the Buddha describes the attitude needed for Vipassana.

37
00:04:50,326 --> 00:04:54,011
First, we need to be ardent.

38
00:04:54,031 --> 00:04:55,952
This indicates a degree of fervour.

39
00:04:56,653 --> 00:04:58,276
We speak of an ardent lover.

40
00:04:59,478 --> 00:05:03,762
We won't gain insight if we are cynical or offhand in our approach.

41
00:05:05,925 --> 00:05:08,509
We need to put our hearts into the practice.

42
00:05:09,468 --> 00:05:14,653
The next phrase can be translated as mindful with clear comprehension.

43
00:05:16,173 --> 00:05:20,737
This corresponds with the factor of investigation in our seven factors.

44
00:05:22,199 --> 00:05:33,509
The phrase ardent, mindful with clear comprehension signifies mindfulness supported by the wide energetic flank of our wild geese.

45
00:05:35,951 --> 00:05:37,432
The final phrase is

46
00:05:38,915 --> 00:05:51,569
Having put aside covetousness and grief with regard to the world, thus we need to let our worldly cares take a back seat for the purpose of practicing Vipassana.

47
00:05:53,072 --> 00:05:55,435
This doesn't mean we suppress our cares.

48
00:05:56,836 --> 00:06:03,084
It means we let them become our focus for meditation whenever they show up.

49
00:06:03,105 --> 00:06:05,968
When grief shows up, we know we are grieving.

50
00:06:07,838 --> 00:06:14,904
Letting our worldly cares be examined like this helps focus the mind and cultivates calm and equanimity.

51
00:06:16,067 --> 00:06:20,550
So here we have the other flank of our wild geese, the slipstream.

52
00:06:23,574 --> 00:06:29,920
The four pastures are body, feeling, mind and dhamma.

53
00:06:31,903 --> 00:06:36,427
It's interesting that the Buddha doesn't list these as four nouns as I've just done.

54
00:06:37,774 --> 00:06:41,901
Lists of nouns tend to objectify and simplify the world.

55
00:06:43,223 --> 00:06:48,473
The way the Buddha puts it tends to draw the world into our inner experience.

56
00:06:50,255 --> 00:06:54,062
He describes them within the meditation practice itself.

57
00:06:56,033 --> 00:07:09,375
Abiku abides contemplating the body as a body, ardent, fully aware and mindful, having put aside covetousness and grief with regard to the world.

58
00:07:11,317 --> 00:07:15,704
He abides contemplating feelings as feelings.

59
00:07:16,826 --> 00:07:18,750
And so on for all four.

60
00:07:19,978 --> 00:07:32,834
Burying the noun within his description of the attitude needed for vipassana suggests that the type of attention we bring into the posture matters as much, if not more, than the posture itself.

61
00:07:35,898 --> 00:07:42,524
The phrases contemplating the body as a body, feelings as feelings, etc.

62
00:07:43,305 --> 00:07:44,788
are also striking.

63
00:07:45,545 --> 00:07:54,338
This indicates our attention needs to sink into these four areas to glean the wisdom offered by their contemplation.

64
00:07:55,819 --> 00:08:03,632
It is only by experiencing them mindfully with clear comprehension that they can deliver us from suffering.

65
00:08:06,456 --> 00:08:11,382
The Sutta then goes on to describe how to practice within each of the pastures.

66
00:08:12,612 --> 00:08:24,608
The section on body contemplation starts with the breath, knowing when we are breathing in and when we're breathing out, knowing when our breath is shallow and when it's deep.

67
00:08:26,670 --> 00:08:36,865
The next steps describe calming ourselves using the breath by bringing the thought of tranquility to mind as we feel the breath rise and fall.

68
00:08:39,224 --> 00:08:47,696
Remember, we talked of the need to calm ourselves whenever the wide flank of our wild geese are rushing ahead and tending to scatter the flock.

69
00:08:49,357 --> 00:08:52,782
So here is the Buddha's suggestion for doing just that.

70
00:08:53,703 --> 00:08:57,208
Noting, calming, calming with each breath.

71
00:09:00,212 --> 00:09:07,121
The next section is described as a refrain because it was repeated again and again throughout the sutta.

72
00:09:08,671 --> 00:09:11,956
It describes the various ways insight can arise.

73
00:09:13,399 --> 00:09:20,711
By insight, we mean a glimpse of some aspect of the Buddha's teaching, for example, the Four Noble Truths.

74
00:09:22,134 --> 00:09:25,278
It may be an insight into the first truth, Dukkha.

75
00:09:26,355 --> 00:09:41,639
We may really feel the changing nature of experience, that all experience is passing away like grains of sand slipping through our fingers, and sense that nothing lasts long enough to satisfy our deep needs for security.

76
00:09:43,942 --> 00:09:49,511
Or we may get a glimpse of the second truth, that desire is the cause of dukkha.

77
00:09:51,263 --> 00:10:01,894
Suppose a memory of some argument has come up and we are embroiled in indignation and anger, insisting over and over again that we were right and the others were wrong.

78
00:10:03,496 --> 00:10:09,443
Every few moments we wake up to what's happening and feel the pain of this experience.

79
00:10:10,365 --> 00:10:14,889
Eventually, worn out and in despair, we give up the battle.

80
00:10:15,991 --> 00:10:18,975
Lo and behold, the pain disappears.

81
00:10:20,304 --> 00:10:26,817
We realise that clinging to the notion, I was right, was what was causing us to suffer.

82
00:10:27,999 --> 00:10:31,063
It wasn't the memory, it was our reaction to it.

83
00:10:32,647 --> 00:10:35,852
That's a direct experience of the second noble truth.

84
00:10:37,294 --> 00:10:39,118
A revolutionary thought surfaces.

85
00:10:40,640 --> 00:10:44,607
Maybe it doesn't matter much which of us was right or wrong.

86
00:10:47,169 --> 00:10:55,446
That moment when the pain disappeared was also an insight into the third noble truth, the fact that dukkha stops.

87
00:10:58,572 --> 00:11:05,787
We need to sensitize ourselves to those lulls in our emotional storms, to start taking them seriously.

88
00:11:07,014 --> 00:11:17,291
Until we're fully enlightened, dukkha will eventually start up again, perhaps as we start craving that this moment of peacefulness will go on forever.

89
00:11:18,793 --> 00:11:20,015
Sad, isn't it?

90
00:11:21,697 --> 00:11:25,464
We have to let peacefulness come and go, just as it will.

91
00:11:26,966 --> 00:11:34,238
Paradoxically, when we can surrender to that sad fact, we experience deeper peace.

92
00:11:37,187 --> 00:11:43,716
At another time, we may get a glimpse of some aspect of the fourth noble truth.

93
00:11:43,736 --> 00:11:54,051
For example, we may be worrying that we're not meditating correctly, feeling nervous and constricted, as if we're going to get thrown out of the dhamma hall any moment.

94
00:11:55,131 --> 00:12:04,544
Then, miraculously it might seem, something changes and we decide, I'm doing okay, this is good enough.

95
00:12:06,466 --> 00:12:09,431
Our hearts lighten, we stop worrying.

96
00:12:10,833 --> 00:12:18,807
Our attention sinks more easily into our breath and we sense the joy of simply being present, breathing.

97
00:12:20,530 --> 00:12:30,870
In that moment we gain confidence that meditation could show us a way towards the end of suffering and we can see the importance of right attitude.

98
00:12:32,250 --> 00:12:37,096
When we were worrying and condemning ourselves, we were caught up in the hindrance of aversion.

99
00:12:38,238 --> 00:12:43,445
When we said, this will do, we were accepting our experience.

100
00:12:45,005 --> 00:12:46,769
That's the only thing that changed.

101
00:12:48,309 --> 00:12:55,339
This gives us a direct insight into the fact that an accepting attitude is integral to the path.

102
00:12:58,947 --> 00:13:03,035
These are some examples of insights that can happen as we meditate.

103
00:13:03,076 --> 00:13:11,335
These kinds of insights can happen while we are following any of the exercises described in the Sutta.

104
00:13:12,577 --> 00:13:17,107
The refrain tells us what to do in order to deepen our insight.

105
00:13:20,091 --> 00:13:22,575
There are three subdivisions to the refrain.

106
00:13:23,596 --> 00:13:32,028
Firstly, the Buddha says, in this way he abides, contemplating the body as a body internally.

107
00:13:34,231 --> 00:13:37,755
Contemplation requires full awareness and understanding.

108
00:13:38,577 --> 00:13:41,120
We're not just vaguely aware of breathing.

109
00:13:42,501 --> 00:13:53,297
The Mahasi noting of the in-breath and out-breath gathers our mind in this way, calming us down and focusing our attention on the experience of breathing.

110
00:13:55,440 --> 00:14:04,412
This first section of the refrain reassures us that gathering the mind and calming ourselves is an integral part of gaining insight.

111
00:14:05,974 --> 00:14:09,859
We don't have to be calm and focused for insight.

112
00:14:10,597 --> 00:14:16,806
they can be sinking in as we are using the breath to encourage ourselves to calm down.

113
00:14:20,330 --> 00:14:25,557
He then says we can practice in this same way, but externally.

114
00:14:27,639 --> 00:14:34,006
The most common interpretation for this is that we contemplate the breathing of another person.

115
00:14:35,606 --> 00:14:47,839
it would take very deep concentration to be able to discern when another person is breathing in or out, a much more challenging practice, which may be why it's so rarely taught.

116
00:14:49,100 --> 00:15:03,994
The next suggestion is even more challenging, to contemplate the body both internally and externally, following our own breath and that of another simultaneously, maybe in our next lifetimes.

117
00:15:05,610 --> 00:15:21,446
And although I won't labour the point, it's worth knowing that he repeats this suggestion for all other exercises in the Sutta, so we can gain insight by bringing awareness to the feelings of others, as well as to their mind states, for example.

118
00:15:23,368 --> 00:15:33,998
Although it would take supernormal powers to be able to directly intuit the feelings and minds of another person, it fosters metta to make any attempt in that direction.

119
00:15:36,610 --> 00:15:41,475
For the purposes of this retreat, we'll confine ourselves to our internal pastures.

120
00:15:42,395 --> 00:15:48,263
But outside of retreat, we can practice becoming more aware of others in this moment-to-moment fashion.

121
00:15:49,443 --> 00:16:02,357
Following their breathing, if we can detect it, their walking, their postures, daily activities and all the other exercises in the Satipatthana Sutta that we'll go through now.

122
00:16:03,619 --> 00:16:06,162
This is a deep form of metta practice.

123
00:16:07,457 --> 00:16:12,845
We have the Buddha's assurance that this is also a perfectly valid form of insight meditation.

124
00:16:16,408 --> 00:16:24,818
So that's the first of the three suggestions in the refrain to bring our full awareness and understanding to the breathing process.

125
00:16:28,524 --> 00:16:35,371
The second suggestion directs our attention to the transitory nature of bodily experience.

126
00:16:35,791 --> 00:16:45,702
each breath arises and passes away and within that each sensation of breathing arises and passes away.

127
00:16:47,505 --> 00:16:52,071
He describes this as the arising and vanishing nature of the body.

128
00:16:54,094 --> 00:16:57,738
He first directs our attention to its arising nature.

129
00:16:59,780 --> 00:17:04,026
Can you sense the breath coming into being each moment?

130
00:17:05,136 --> 00:17:07,700
The in-breath is particularly useful here.

131
00:17:09,101 --> 00:17:15,248
See can you feel its first manifestation and how it then continues to swell the body.

132
00:17:18,030 --> 00:17:23,557
Next he directs attention to what he terms the body in its nature of vanishing.

133
00:17:25,019 --> 00:17:28,663
One breath vanishes before the next one can appear.

134
00:17:29,385 --> 00:17:35,653
The out-breath is most helpful here, following its movement moment after moment until it stops.

135
00:17:39,077 --> 00:17:44,404
His next suggestion is to be aware of both the arising and passing nature of the body.

136
00:17:45,446 --> 00:17:51,914
Here we sense the full breath, in and out, as a flow of discrete sensations.

137
00:17:52,895 --> 00:17:55,900
As one vanishes, the next arises.

138
00:17:58,494 --> 00:18:04,307
These three exercises help us to see the truth of anicca, transience.

139
00:18:06,070 --> 00:18:14,808
Although our minds project continuity and permanence into the world, the experiential truth is that things are constantly changing.

140
00:18:15,510 --> 00:18:18,596
They arise and a moment later they vanish.

141
00:18:20,128 --> 00:18:29,531
We can nudge our minds towards this truth by experiencing the breath arising and passing as the Buddha suggests in the Satipatthana Sutta.

142
00:18:33,190 --> 00:18:38,038
His final suggestion for insight is simply to be aware of our bodies.

143
00:18:39,321 --> 00:18:51,164
In the Buddha's words, mindfulness that there is a body is simply established in him to the extent necessary for bare knowledge and mindfulness.

144
00:18:53,390 --> 00:18:57,074
This suggests a very light touch, bare knowledge.

145
00:18:58,276 --> 00:19:11,130
It's quite a contrast to the first suggestion, to abide contemplating the body as a body, which suggests more energetic gathering of our powers of attention and understanding.

146
00:19:13,413 --> 00:19:17,076
So, we have the three suggestions for gaining insight.

147
00:19:18,038 --> 00:19:21,642
The first involves calming and focusing the mind on the body.

148
00:19:22,718 --> 00:19:25,540
The second explores its transitory nature.

149
00:19:25,601 --> 00:19:30,467
The third simply requires bare knowledge of the body.

150
00:19:33,310 --> 00:19:40,960
The first describes the active effort we need to make to calm ourselves and steady attention within the felt sense of breathing.

151
00:19:42,020 --> 00:19:46,886
Here we're working on the slipstream flank of our wild geese.

152
00:19:48,959 --> 00:19:54,704
Once we're settled, we can afford to open our minds to be more exploratory.

153
00:19:55,786 --> 00:19:58,169
So this is where his second suggestion comes in.

154
00:19:59,470 --> 00:20:02,292
We explore the transitory nature of experience.

155
00:20:03,795 --> 00:20:08,680
This is the particular expertise of our wide flank, the ones that push us ahead.

156
00:20:10,361 --> 00:20:18,509
At times our minds come to a point of delicate balance and we sense mindful investigation carrying on of its own accord.

157
00:20:19,924 --> 00:20:25,478
We sense any attempt we make to either calm or probe more deeply as slightly disturbing.

158
00:20:27,061 --> 00:20:29,247
So we can refrain from any effort.

159
00:20:31,191 --> 00:20:36,262
At this stage, the third suggestion, bear attention, comes into play.

160
00:20:39,127 --> 00:20:43,795
At times this kind of exploration pulls us towards a deep state of peace .

161
00:20:45,817 --> 00:20:47,519
Sometimes it's the opposite.

162
00:20:48,221 --> 00:20:52,307
We get fearful and all kinds of underlying emotions come to the surface.

163
00:20:53,567 --> 00:20:58,275
In both cases the third suggestion of bare knowledge can be applied.

164
00:20:59,557 --> 00:21:00,878
Take the emotional storm.

165
00:21:01,779 --> 00:21:05,945
This can batter us with wild thoughts and painful feelings.

166
00:21:06,449 --> 00:21:14,482
But so long as we're aware of a body that exists in the midst of it all, we're still on the direct path to enlightenment.

167
00:21:15,744 --> 00:21:24,339
We're in the pasture and our intelligence is open to insight even in the midst of a hurricane of anger or lust.

168
00:21:26,040 --> 00:21:28,486
We're not doing any deep investigation.

169
00:21:29,067 --> 00:21:31,872
It's just the lightest touch of body awareness.

170
00:21:33,094 --> 00:21:36,942
The geese are flapping around at a great rate, devouring the weeds.

171
00:21:40,387 --> 00:21:47,121
Bare knowledge of the body also grounds us when the mind is being drawn towards the calm of a jhana.

172
00:21:47,911 --> 00:21:52,977
In these states, we can lose touch altogether with our bodily sensations.

173
00:21:54,238 --> 00:21:57,682
The danger is that we also lose any degree of intelligence.

174
00:21:59,222 --> 00:22:05,390
If we have to keep remembering our physical nature, we would be bringing wisdom into the realm of Jahana.

175
00:22:07,011 --> 00:22:15,201
Our slipstream geese are lulling us to sleep, but the wide flank have just enough energy to keep prodding us awake.

176
00:22:18,673 --> 00:22:25,925
So no matter what aspect of the four pastures you are examining, you always have three choices for how to attend.

177
00:22:27,868 --> 00:22:33,919
You can calm and gather your attention by focusing on any of the exercises suggested in the Sutta.

178
00:22:35,682 --> 00:22:41,391
When your attention is steady, you can examine the transitory nature of your experience.

179
00:22:42,890 --> 00:22:51,201
The final option, bare attention, applies when there is that knife edge of balance between calm and curiosity.

180
00:22:52,622 --> 00:22:57,729
It grounds you through temptations to drift into an emotion or jhana state.

181
00:23:02,013 --> 00:23:10,585
The Buddha's final comment in the refrain is that he abides independent, not clinging to anything in the world.

182
00:23:12,640 --> 00:23:17,266
This is a reminder not to identify with whatever it is we are experiencing.

183
00:23:18,086 --> 00:23:20,169
Remember it's all going to change.

184
00:23:21,451 --> 00:23:30,000
If we cling to joy, calm or clarity, we will later be screaming with frustration when these are so unfairly taken from us.

185
00:23:31,762 --> 00:23:37,230
If we resist states like confusion and agitation, we unwittingly prolong them.

186
00:23:38,375 --> 00:23:54,442
In contrast, relaxing into them shows us that they also are composed of sensations and feelings which simply arise and pass away, nothing to be worried about, just another hillock in our pasture.

187
00:23:56,626 --> 00:24:01,075
All states can deliver the insight we need for liberation.

188
00:24:03,501 --> 00:24:04,702
So that's the refrain.

189
00:24:04,722 --> 00:24:09,327
The various suggestions for how we look at our experience.

190
00:24:11,290 --> 00:24:14,934
The Sutta then goes back to describing what it is we look at.

191
00:24:16,596 --> 00:24:18,178
First, we had the breath.

192
00:24:19,839 --> 00:24:25,987
The Buddha next goes on to describe four bodily postures as foundations for mindfulness.

193
00:24:26,807 --> 00:24:30,791
Standing, sitting, walking or lying down.

194
00:24:32,694 --> 00:24:36,117
The next section describes more broad-based mindfulness.

195
00:24:37,338 --> 00:24:48,109
Being fully aware when we are looking about, moving around, eating, drinking, talking, keeping silent, even defecating and urinating are included.

196
00:24:49,411 --> 00:24:51,532
This covers all of our daily life.

197
00:24:53,234 --> 00:24:56,157
After both sections the refrain is repeated in full.

198
00:24:57,759 --> 00:25:00,761
We might have an abanic insight as we're sitting on the loo.

199
00:25:04,251 --> 00:25:08,258
The next section involves the use of thought or mental images.

200
00:25:09,659 --> 00:25:12,022
We bring to mind the various parts of the body.

201
00:25:12,943 --> 00:25:25,260
Hair on the head, body hair, nails, teeth, skin and all the way through the major organs and down to spittle, snot, oil of the joints and urine.

202
00:25:26,623 --> 00:25:29,205
We don't often dwell on the separate parts of the body.

203
00:25:29,807 --> 00:25:33,211
The exercise can stir disgust or fear.

204
00:25:34,390 --> 00:25:40,134
But of course these can be experienced mindfully as a means of purifying our relationship with our bodies.

205
00:25:41,737 --> 00:25:48,001
We lose some level of deluded identification with our physical body as we go through this contemplation.

206
00:25:49,223 --> 00:26:04,076
Disgust changes to humble appreciation as we realise that our path to liberation depends on entities like snot, spittle, oil of the joints and urine as they do their quiet work to keep us alive.

207
00:26:09,862 --> 00:26:20,257
The next section is more appealing, contemplating the body in terms of the four elements, earth, water, air and fire.

208
00:26:23,181 --> 00:26:30,830
While the previous exercise involves the faculty of thought and imagination, this exercise involves physical experience.

209
00:26:32,272 --> 00:26:38,501
The earth element describes the experiences of hardness, softness, weight and pressure.

210
00:26:39,577 --> 00:26:42,682
For example, try this exercise just now.

211
00:26:43,984 --> 00:26:46,588
Gently squeeze one hand within the other.

212
00:26:48,692 --> 00:26:52,878
Can you feel areas of bony hardness and fleshy softness?

213
00:26:54,780 --> 00:26:55,903
Squeeze more tightly.

214
00:26:57,005 --> 00:26:58,126
Can you feel the pressure?

215
00:27:01,311 --> 00:27:03,234
Try lifting one hand in the other.

216
00:27:04,296 --> 00:27:05,518
Can you feel its weight?

217
00:27:09,109 --> 00:27:12,994
All these are explorations of the earth element in your body.

218
00:27:16,178 --> 00:27:23,287
The water element is easier to experience externally as you're washing the dishes, for example, or taking a shower.

219
00:27:24,567 --> 00:27:29,714
Feel the way it flows around you, always changing its course to suit your shape.

220
00:27:30,875 --> 00:27:34,480
It can also be sensed as the fluidity in the movement of joints.

221
00:27:35,801 --> 00:27:37,564
Try rotating your wrist

222
00:27:39,873 --> 00:27:42,275
Can you sense the fluidity required for this?

223
00:27:45,378 --> 00:27:46,539
Rotate your shoulders.

224
00:27:48,882 --> 00:27:52,746
It couldn't happen if the bones weren't separated by layer of fluid.

225
00:27:55,469 --> 00:27:57,750
The air element is sensed in movement.

226
00:27:58,971 --> 00:28:01,273
Gently move your hands or arms now.

227
00:28:04,057 --> 00:28:05,578
How do you sense movement?

228
00:28:06,660 --> 00:28:07,820
Isn't it very subtle?

229
00:28:09,438 --> 00:28:10,398
as light as air.

230
00:28:12,402 --> 00:28:18,510
You can explore this during walking meditation, especially when the foot is moving forward.

231
00:28:21,955 --> 00:28:27,064
The last of the elements is fire, which describes our sense of temperature.

232
00:28:28,645 --> 00:28:31,068
This includes both heat and coolness.

233
00:28:32,832 --> 00:28:36,356
Scan your body now to see if any areas feel warm.

234
00:28:40,369 --> 00:28:42,452
Try putting your hands on your face.

235
00:28:45,698 --> 00:28:51,488
Often there's a difference in temperature and so we feel both warmth and coolness.

236
00:28:53,351 --> 00:28:56,635
It can be hard to work out which part is cool and which is warm.

237
00:28:59,740 --> 00:29:04,268
Whenever you go outdoors see can you sense any change in temperature.

238
00:29:07,926 --> 00:29:13,354
I find the exercise on the elements helps my attention to dwell on the body for longer periods.

239
00:29:14,555 --> 00:29:21,083
By contrast, the next exercise is more likely to shoot my attention outwards into clouds of thought.

240
00:29:22,265 --> 00:29:24,346
This is the contemplation on death.

241
00:29:26,549 --> 00:29:32,297
In the Buddha's time, human bodies were left to decay in open areas called charnel grounds.

242
00:29:33,204 --> 00:29:36,810
He asked his followers to go there and watch the process of decay.

243
00:29:36,851 --> 00:29:44,284
Although this sounds horrific, the purpose is to meet our fear of death and come to terms with our mortality.

244
00:29:45,846 --> 00:29:55,382
We can practice this contemplation on death by reminding ourselves that our bodies too will fall ill, grow old and eventually die.

245
00:29:57,269 --> 00:30:13,404
If we can bear mindfully with any emotional responses, we may eventually come round to a deeper appreciation for the body in its present live and functional state, and a determination to make the best of this short stay on earth that we have been offered.

246
00:30:17,429 --> 00:30:27,259
After each of these exercises, the Buddha repeats the refrain, emphasizing that insight can be gained as we do any of these.

247
00:30:29,617 --> 00:30:32,321
This brings to an end the section on the body.

248
00:30:34,625 --> 00:30:52,571
All of these exercises in this first posture require that attention rest at the point of sense contact in the wheel of dependent origination, in this case involving sense contact from seeing, hearing, tasting, smelling and touching.

249
00:30:53,969 --> 00:31:05,923
Sense contact, the midpoint of the wheel, is where our inner world, our potential, finds an outlet to explore and perhaps express itself in the outer world.

250
00:31:08,146 --> 00:31:14,454
If we can ground ourselves at sense contact, the wheel can't turn all the way to dukkha.

251
00:31:15,957 --> 00:31:20,482
Our wild geese are pecking at the weeds the moment they show their head above ground.

252
00:31:26,015 --> 00:31:36,450
The Buddha then goes on to describe the next posture for mindfulness, feeling, which, as you may remember, is the next link in the wheel of dependent origination.

253
00:31:38,432 --> 00:31:45,041
Once our senses have made contact, we then categorise the sensation as pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

254
00:31:46,723 --> 00:31:51,009
In Buddhism, that basic categorisation is what we mean by feeling.

255
00:31:52,913 --> 00:31:59,959
When the mind is tending to wander easily it is often helpful to ask what feeling is fueling these thoughts?

256
00:32:01,500 --> 00:32:10,588
This can draw us towards the root of the problem as it is our reaction to feeling that drives the wheel to the wandering mind and thereby to dukkha.

257
00:32:12,510 --> 00:32:21,739
Often there will be a zone of tension in the body corresponding to the attempt to cling to pleasure or get rid of unpleasant feelings.

258
00:32:22,984 --> 00:32:25,847
The emotion underlying the thoughts has its root here.

259
00:32:26,909 --> 00:32:35,137
If we can bring attention to that area of the body, we get a sense of ourselves clinging to some feeling at the centre of the knot.

260
00:32:36,338 --> 00:32:39,522
At that stage, our thoughts often quieten down.

261
00:32:41,243 --> 00:32:43,507
However, this is not an easy process.

262
00:32:44,988 --> 00:32:49,313
Feeling is a more subtle level of experience than sense contact.

263
00:32:50,541 --> 00:32:55,249
We need a degree of calm and equanimity to be able to steady the mind on feelings.

264
00:32:56,652 --> 00:32:58,795
So have patience with this posture.

265
00:33:00,417 --> 00:33:01,920
Coming back to our wild geese.

266
00:33:02,842 --> 00:33:08,891
When emotions run deep, the wide flank tends to go a bit wild when I turn attention on feelings.

267
00:33:10,173 --> 00:33:12,135
So it needs constant rebalancing.

268
00:33:13,198 --> 00:33:15,080
The body is a great help here.

269
00:33:15,500 --> 00:33:22,047
Coming back again and again to the sensations of breath or of posture takes the heat out of the situation.

270
00:33:22,988 --> 00:33:24,810
Slowly, slowly, catchy monkey.

271
00:33:26,551 --> 00:33:44,712
After some perseverance, attention may be able to rest in or near the physical sensations associated with the emotion and be able to detect their pleasantness and the tendency to grasp onto this or their unpleasantness and the tendency to push these away.

272
00:33:48,135 --> 00:33:53,426
The third category of feeling, neutral feeling, won't be at the core of emotional tension.

273
00:33:54,609 --> 00:33:57,757
We don't try to grasp or push away neutral feeling.

274
00:33:58,657 --> 00:34:00,803
The habitual reaction is to ignore it.

275
00:34:02,046 --> 00:34:07,376
We're working with neutral feelings when we're persuading our attention to rest on the breath and the footsteps.

276
00:34:08,690 --> 00:34:18,644
Our difficulty in holding attention steady is not that we dislike or are enthralled by the physical sensations, but that we want a more exciting focus.

277
00:34:20,927 --> 00:34:27,538
Although it can be quite a challenge to get our attention to rest calmly in this posture, the pickings are very rich.

278
00:34:28,860 --> 00:34:38,494
We're learning not to identify with our feelings, letting go of the habitual reactions of desire, aversion and ignoring.

279
00:34:42,371 --> 00:34:55,257
I'll say more about feelings tomorrow night, but for the moment I just want to mention that in this Sutta the Buddha also points out another distinction in feeling between worldly and unworldly feelings.

280
00:34:56,719 --> 00:34:59,385
Worldly feelings are based on sense contact.

281
00:35:00,461 --> 00:35:03,985
Unworldly feelings are associated with spiritual endeavour.

282
00:35:04,867 --> 00:35:12,416
For example, generosity, metta, compassion, meditative joy are all unworldly feelings.

283
00:35:13,777 --> 00:35:25,070
They also happen to be pleasant feelings, and of course there's a danger that we cling to them unwittingly, thinking, I am generous, I am filled with loving kindness, etc.

284
00:35:26,532 --> 00:35:29,574
This feels fine until something bursts that bubble.

285
00:35:30,938 --> 00:35:34,262
The fall to earth can be very sore and bring out the worst in us.

286
00:35:34,983 --> 00:35:36,726
Suddenly we hate everyone.

287
00:35:38,949 --> 00:35:47,922
But if we can be mindful of the pleasant feeling, we can appreciate it and use it to fuel our generosity and metta and all other beautiful states.

288
00:35:51,726 --> 00:35:55,512
There can also be unpleasant feelings that come from spiritual endeavour.

289
00:35:56,588 --> 00:36:04,018
For example, we may feel ashamed or depressed because our minds keep wandering or because we can't understand the Dhamma.

290
00:36:05,219 --> 00:36:10,847
The big danger, of course, is to identify with these feelings and let ourselves become discouraged.

291
00:36:12,429 --> 00:36:18,559
But if we can open to the feelings, they can bring up a tender compassion for our unenlightened state.

292
00:36:20,282 --> 00:36:24,367
This is quite a deep degree of self-acknowledgement and self-care.

293
00:36:25,248 --> 00:36:26,190
Very healing.

294
00:36:27,367 --> 00:36:41,344
Once we sense this, the very unpleasantness locks us into the compassionate response and thereby propels us along the path.

295
00:36:41,364 --> 00:36:45,248
Neutral unworldly feelings are associated with equanimity.

296
00:36:46,851 --> 00:36:53,898
If we don't notice these, we can set up a subtle level of clinging, thinking, I am equanimous.

297
00:36:54,907 --> 00:36:57,635
But of course, this bubble also bursts in time.

298
00:36:58,938 --> 00:37:05,795
If we acknowledge the neutral feelings, these can release us into a wise appreciation of equanimity.

299
00:37:11,242 --> 00:37:15,967
The Buddha again repeats the refrain after describing this second posture.

300
00:37:16,027 --> 00:37:31,420
Here he is clarifying that we can gain the insight needed for liberation by knowing whether we are feeling a pleasant, unpleasant or neutral feeling and knowing whether it comes from sense contact or spiritual endeavour.

301
00:37:33,021 --> 00:37:39,427
Similarly we can study transience in our feelings noticing that these two arise and pass away

302
00:37:40,672 --> 00:37:51,025
As for the body, the third possibility is to simply note there are feelings, without any attempt to categorise or detect their transient nature.

303
00:37:55,891 --> 00:37:59,554
The next section of the Sutta involves contemplating our mind.

304
00:38:00,675 --> 00:38:06,563
This involves, for example, knowing when we're angry or greedy, and all the variations on these.

305
00:38:07,706 --> 00:38:14,657
For example, anger may take on hues of irritation, fear, frustration, jealousy or cruelty.

306
00:38:16,059 --> 00:38:22,969
Greed can take the form of excitement, romance, lust, euphoria or passionate attachment.

307
00:38:24,632 --> 00:38:34,407
To correlate this with the wheel of dependent origination, we're now focusing on the early stages of the wheel, the stages prior to sense contact.

308
00:38:35,534 --> 00:38:39,237
These make up the attitude we bring into being at the point of contact.

309
00:38:40,398 --> 00:38:48,887
We think we see and hear things objectively, but in fact our perception is coloured by whatever mind state is driving us to sense contact.

310
00:38:50,929 --> 00:38:54,512
I had a good illustration of this one time when doing walking meditation.

311
00:38:55,813 --> 00:39:02,739
It was a big airy room and I had been alone until someone came in and started walking quite close nearby.

312
00:39:04,728 --> 00:39:07,202
I felt myself contract in aversion.

313
00:39:08,389 --> 00:39:11,768
At the same time I could have sworn the room went dark.

314
00:39:13,148 --> 00:39:21,143
I had experienced the darkening of the room and the darkening of my mind simultaneously, and could intuitively sense their connection.

315
00:39:22,445 --> 00:39:27,454
Nevertheless, I couldn't quite believe that my perceptions could be so easily modified.

316
00:39:28,556 --> 00:39:33,126
I looked out the window to check whether a big rain cloud had appeared, but it hadn't.

317
00:39:33,766 --> 00:39:35,190
The sky was still blue.

318
00:39:35,170 --> 00:39:50,530
reluctantly i accepted that even my perception of light could be influenced by my mood i was quite dismayed the outside world wasn't quite so stable and objectively real as i had believed

319
00:39:54,509 --> 00:40:02,500
When we dwell mindfully in this pasture, we are noting what moods or mind states we're bringing to being at every point of sense contact.

320
00:40:03,681 --> 00:40:06,125
Otherwise, we're being controlled by the mind state.

321
00:40:06,686 --> 00:40:10,371
It is driving us into thought and action, but we're not conscious of this.

322
00:40:11,172 --> 00:40:12,373
We believe the thoughts.

323
00:40:13,614 --> 00:40:22,407
For example, something irritates us and we grow tense in indignation, generating thoughts like, ''It's not fair.''

324
00:40:22,387 --> 00:40:28,853
The resulting unpleasant feelings of tension prompt us to think yet again that it's not fair.

325
00:40:30,755 --> 00:40:35,181
So we think the thoughts again and again convincing ourselves of their truth.

326
00:40:36,501 --> 00:40:42,487
The thoughts fuel the underlying emotion and so we get more deeply caught in the negative spiral.

327
00:40:45,672 --> 00:40:51,398
The first step is to replace the thought stream with the noting word thinking, thinking.

328
00:40:52,744 --> 00:40:55,568
This takes one level of feedback out of the loop.

329
00:40:56,811 --> 00:41:00,255
The body is our great ally in coming close to the root of the problem.

330
00:41:01,657 --> 00:41:05,202
We might need to calm for a while, using the breath for example.

331
00:41:06,344 --> 00:41:12,574
Then, if we can feel where the body is tensing, this draws our attention towards the underlying emotion.

332
00:41:13,275 --> 00:41:16,980
We can simply note feeling, feeling here.

333
00:41:18,782 --> 00:41:23,630
But sometimes getting the right noting word is like hitting the nail on the head.

334
00:41:24,873 --> 00:41:27,617
All the mind state really wants is recognition.

335
00:41:29,340 --> 00:41:35,530
The more often we bring attention into this posture, the better we get at discerning our moods and emotions.

336
00:41:36,672 --> 00:41:45,246
In this case, for example, noting indignation might bring a palpable release of that pent-up energy.

337
00:41:46,541 --> 00:41:55,043
However, if the emotion runs deep, we must be patient and keep on noting while it eventually burns itself out.

338
00:41:56,726 --> 00:42:03,083
And moments last in mindfulness and we will be building up the story of how unfair life is again.

339
00:42:07,264 --> 00:42:09,367
The Buddha's advice is very simple.

340
00:42:10,369 --> 00:42:16,556
For example, he notes a mind affected by anger as a mind affected by anger.

341
00:42:18,016 --> 00:42:19,639
There is no judgment required.

342
00:42:20,880 --> 00:42:25,244
Simple acknowledgement of our afflicted mind states is all that is required.

343
00:42:26,447 --> 00:42:28,648
Judgment tends to contract us further.

344
00:42:30,231 --> 00:42:34,655
But of course, we can't undo our habit of judging so easily.

345
00:42:37,757 --> 00:42:56,045
So whenever we sense that we're adding the second arrow of self-judgment, we simply let attention graze in the feel of judgment, feeling its physical expression in our bodies as well as whatever emotions show up, disapproval, self-disgust, self-hatred.

346
00:42:57,367 --> 00:43:00,931
From the point of view of insight, all these are equally welcome.

347
00:43:02,333 --> 00:43:05,097
Wisdom grows as we witness these.

348
00:43:09,769 --> 00:43:15,719
The Sutta also advises us to note the absence of mind states like greed and anger.

349
00:43:15,780 --> 00:43:18,744
This isn't something we often do.

350
00:43:18,784 --> 00:43:25,094
We tend only to notice our minds when they're troubled, not when they're clear and at ease.

351
00:43:26,137 --> 00:43:30,545
But noticing the absence of trouble helps us appreciate those states.

352
00:43:31,786 --> 00:43:37,956
We find it easier to let go of excitement, for example, when we learn to appreciate the pleasantness of being calm.

353
00:43:39,297 --> 00:43:41,722
Just now, for example, are you angry?

354
00:43:43,463 --> 00:43:50,474
If not, note, not angry, not angry, and get a felt sense of that mental state.

355
00:43:52,193 --> 00:43:57,898
Similarly, you could ask yourself if your mind is excited, wanting more stimulation.

356
00:43:59,460 --> 00:44:03,646
If not, note, not excited, not excited.

357
00:44:04,967 --> 00:44:07,911
We need to get to know these unobtrusive mind states.

358
00:44:09,211 --> 00:44:10,974
Our minds like familiarity.

359
00:44:12,255 --> 00:44:17,762
What the mind knows and is familiar with, it comes back to again and again.

360
00:44:21,050 --> 00:44:30,099
Apart from the variations on greed and anger, our minds can be deluded, thinking there is a very powerful me in control of all my experience.

361
00:44:31,521 --> 00:44:35,304
Again, we can simply note this as delusion, delusion.

362
00:44:36,706 --> 00:44:43,932
The belief and the felt experience may be the same, but they have now been brought within the pasture for wisdom to graze upon.

363
00:44:45,934 --> 00:44:49,639
Very gradually the wild geese nibble away at our delusions.

364
00:44:50,952 --> 00:45:01,789
Similarly, we can note the presence or absence of sleepiness, restlessness, distraction, concentration, peacefulness and any mind state.

365
00:45:06,494 --> 00:45:25,260
The Buddha then repeats the refrain reiterating that insight can be gained as we note the presence or absence of our mind states as we sense them arise and pass away or as we simply ground ourselves in the knowledge that there is a mind without any attempt to be more discerning than that.

366
00:45:28,385 --> 00:45:35,876
The latter is the kind of light touch mindfulness we need when any attempt to probe more deeply would disturb the experience.

367
00:45:39,181 --> 00:45:45,250
The final pasture is called Dhammas and there's a lot of controversy about how to translate this.

368
00:45:46,311 --> 00:45:56,768
The Dhamma is the teaching of the Buddha and is usually spelled with a capital D. But the word Dhammas here is plural and with a small d.

369
00:45:57,862 --> 00:46:01,668
The classical translation is mind objects.

370
00:46:01,688 --> 00:46:06,735
But that's not very helpful since all the other pastures can also be described as mind objects.

371
00:46:07,456 --> 00:46:12,605
We make the body, feelings and mind into objects for contemplation in those pastures.

372
00:46:14,447 --> 00:46:19,014
Recently the translation categories of experience is gaining favour.

373
00:46:20,157 --> 00:46:21,539
But that's not very elegant.

374
00:46:22,360 --> 00:46:23,581
It's hard to relate to.

375
00:46:24,811 --> 00:46:30,501
Looking ahead to see what the pastor describes, it is actually a number of the Buddha's teachings.

376
00:46:31,903 --> 00:46:42,364
The teachings he picks out include the hindrances, the factors of enlightenment and the four noble truths, as well as two more which we'll discuss over the next two evenings.

377
00:46:44,690 --> 00:46:56,876
In my simple way of thinking, I can see why we don't call this pasture the Dhamma, because here we are in fact contemplating the central core of the Buddha's teachings.

378
00:46:58,038 --> 00:47:10,735
Whatever we call it, this last pasture asks us to let our attention dwell on the moment-to-moment experience of the hindrances, factors of enlightenment, four noble truths and other teachings.

379
00:47:12,199 --> 00:47:20,130
This makes it abundantly clear that these teachings are not simply lists of human attributes or philosophical statements.

380
00:47:20,110 --> 00:47:31,784
The Satipatthana Sutta clarifies that we must know and understand these teachings within the realm of our individual subjective experience.

381
00:47:33,246 --> 00:47:47,585
We are to let our attention dwell on these teachings as they manifest in our body and mind, ingesting their wisdom moment by moment until we eventually see these from the Buddha's point of view.

382
00:47:49,085 --> 00:47:52,496
This is what it means to be a follower of the Buddha.

383
00:47:55,530 --> 00:48:02,983
I'm not going to say any more about this pasture tonight, because all the teachings mentioned here are explored in other talks.

384
00:48:04,425 --> 00:48:21,994
Let's just skip to the conclusion of the Sutta, where the Buddha assures us that if we can explore our experience, according to Satipatthana's Sutta, for just seven days, we will have deep, deep insight, perhaps even full liberation.

385
00:48:22,902 --> 00:48:26,565
Luckily, there are still seven days left in this retreat.

386
00:48:27,867 --> 00:48:29,469
So now you know what you have to do.

387
00:48:31,231 --> 00:48:34,675
Persuade yourself to be an ardent lover of truth.

388
00:48:35,938 --> 00:48:38,840
Bring your mindful intelligence to the quest for truth.

389
00:48:40,222 --> 00:48:48,353
Put aside your worldly cares, or if they refuse to subside, let them become the focus for meditation.

390
00:48:50,003 --> 00:48:53,228
Draw your mind into whichever posture beckons you.

391
00:48:54,269 --> 00:49:00,639
When you're settled, start exploring the transient nature of your experience.

392
00:49:02,041 --> 00:49:09,092
Lighten the attention to bare registration of the posture when you feel that would suit the situation best.

393
00:49:10,795 --> 00:49:11,376
That's all.

394
00:49:12,679 --> 00:49:15,724
As Bhante would say, easy-weezy-peasy.

395
00:49:18,302 --> 00:49:26,119
May your exploration of the four pastures for mindfulness bring you to full enlightenment in this very lifetime.

